ndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1911 one of every three Canadians lived in urban areas; today three out of four do. This growth has raised serious issues in urban government: How should power and authority be distributed among differing, often competing, urban interests? How can municipal governments obtain the funds they need to satisfy the increased demand for community and social services? How much should citizens participate? At a conference held in Banff on alternate forms of urban government, academics and practitioners considered these, and other pressing urban problems. Problems of change in urban government, presents the results of the conference, along with other, related essays. The contributors are Lloyd Axworthy, Meyer Brownstone, Stephen Clarkson, J.A. Johnson, James Lorimer, Allan O’Brien, T.J. Plunkett, Louise Quesnel-Ouellet, Paul Tennant, and the volume editors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdministration municipalexCongrèsxCanada. 0aAgglomérations urbainesxAdministrationxCongrèsxCanada. 0aFinances municipalesxCongrèsxCanadaxCanadaxConference papers and proceedings. 0aMetropolitan governmentxCongressesxCanada. 0aMetropolitan governmentzCanadavCongresses. 0aMunicipal financexCongressesxCanada. 0aMunicipal financezCanadavCongresses. 0aMunicipal governmentxCongressesxCanada. 0aMunicipal governmentzCanadavCongresses. 4aPolitical Science. 4aSocial Science: Development Studies. 4aSocial Science: Urban Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Local.2bisacsh1 aAxworthy, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownstone, Meyer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarkson, Stephen, econtributor.4ct